Make the stdio bridge dispatch every JSON-RPC request at most once.

Only the side-effect-free readiness probe is retried while a daemon starts or
a sibling bridge occupies its event loop. After readiness, init, stop, and
JSON-RPC expressions run exactly once. A bounded JSON parser preserves exact
top-level request ids and recognizes initialize without trusting nested fields.
Ambiguous post-dispatch failures produce correlated structured errors with
phase/dispatched/replayed fields instead of replaying a mutation.

Every external program runs under a Bash-owned deadline implemented with process
substitution and builtin read -t, so a loader-frozen child is bounded without GNU
timeout. When configured, the parent guard validates the runner's pre-dispatch
numeric identity, arms pidfd/kqueue before moving the target process group, and
reaps that group on runner or bridge death. Stateful stderr uses a process-lifetime
sink FD. After dispatch, response validation, normalization, UTF-8 byte framing,
NUL rejection, and bounded-chunk streaming use Bash builtins only, including on
macOS Bash 3.2. Incomplete frames fail closed rather than desynchronizing the pipe.

